@node intro "Introduction"

NSA Wall was created purely because of a lack of a decent scene style
wall for Paragon compatable systems!!!

Ami Express has probably the best wall going (LSD Wall) which I used to run
on my BBS until my /X emulator for MAX's Pro shagged up :/
(I will fix it ready for the release tho!)

Anyway, I was on the hunt for a decent wall as a replacement...  Each had
their problems!

DCwall 4000 - Written in AMOS 1.3 so can't be multi-patched for a 2 node BBS.
UltraWall - Just doesn't have the look & feel of a scene wall.
(It is a good wall for max's tho!  check it out if you don't like NSA Wall!)

And of course there's hundreds of shite attempts at a wall going around,
but those aren't even de-archiving :/

So I wrote my own :)

NSA Wall is a PARAGON door!  It'll work with virtually **ANY** Amiga BBS
system!

It has been tested with MAX's, MAX's BBS Professional & Zeus BBS v1.1.

It should also run perfectly on /X, DayDream, Cnet, DLG etc etc etc...

Hell, if it runs on a piece of crap like Zeus, it WILL run on anything :)

@endnode
@node sysreq "System Requirements"

You MUST have a BBS system capable to using Paragon doors.

MOST Amiga BBS systems have a facility of doing this :)

Also owning an Amiga is a good start too :) hehehehhe

@endnode
@node inst "Installation & Configs"

The easy bit :^)... Just use the following:-

	Lha X NSA_Wall.Lha Doors:
	
This will work for any system that has Doors: assigned to where the BBS has
it's doors..


Running
~~~~~~~

Execution under MAX's BBS (All versions) & MAX's BBS Professional
In the menu editor set.

Key:   Function:  Extra:    Lo Acc:    Hi Acc:	  Filename/Name/Dest/Path:
 W       34	    0 	      1 	10000	  Doors:NSA_Wall/NSA_Wall


Each BBS system has a differant way of running Paragon doors, please
consult your BBS manual for more information :)

It's a good idea to change the ANSI file supplied with this door!!!!

Otherwise peeps will think they've called Redrum :)


ANSI's
~~~~~~

NSA wall requires 3 ANSI files to operate!

TopBanner.Wall
Wall.Wall
BottomBanner.Wall

TopBanner.wall is a 3 line high ANSI file for the top of the display :)
Wall.wall is 15 lines high!  It's the backdrop for the wall writing.
BottomBanner.Wall is the 3 line high ANSI for use at the bottom of the wall.

Please change these to suit your BBS :)

@endnode

@node inuse "Using NSA Wall when started :))))))"

When first run, NSA Wall creates a blank wall.data for for storing its data.

The wall then displays itself and presents a user with the following prompt:-

Write On The Wall? (Yes/No) :

If the user presses Y then they are asked for a message to be printed...
After a message has been entered, they will be asked for a name to be
displayed..  This is like.

1. Real Name   2. Anonymous   3. Change  (1/2/3) :

Afterwards, the user can select which colour they want the writing in by
using the space bar to cycle through the colours :))))


Anyone with sysop access will see a differant start!


Write On The Wall? (Yes/No/View anon/Delete line) :

`View anon' lets the sysop see who really wrote what :))

`Delete line' brings up another menu where yo uselect a line to delete
via the cursor keys & hit return to delete the line.


Auto Inserts!
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

NSA Wall can handle auto-inserts within lines :)

The % inserts are removed on MAX's BBS systems, but kept on all others.

The following are supported by NSA-Wall :-

<** USER **>  - Shows the current user's name
<** PHONE **> - Shows the user's phone number
<** AREA **>  - Shows the users location :)

These MUST be typed in caps!!!!!!

eg...

"Keep an eye out for <** USER **>...  He smells!"

would turn into...

"Keep an eye out for Fred Bloggs...  He smells!"

Just a quick example eh? :)


As you can imagine, auto-inserts are a good way to start arguements :)


I think that's about it now :)))))))))))))

(Read the credz & greetz :))) )


@endnode

